WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.000
Front.

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:09.740
All right, well, thank you guys so much for having me.

00:00:09.740 --> 00:00:12.920
Hello, from sunny California.

00:00:12.920 --> 00:00:18.120
I'm really excited to be able to come and talk with you remotely about some work that

00:00:18.120 --> 00:00:21.520
happened regarding dynamic interactions.

00:00:21.520 --> 00:00:25.920
So we're basically taking Quarto documents that you know and love, and that you saw a

00:00:25.920 --> 00:00:29.879
lot of really great features get developed for, and we're allowing them to become a lot

00:00:29.879 --> 00:00:32.880
more interactive using WebR.

00:00:32.880 --> 00:00:36.880
So before we begin, though, a few quick things.

00:00:36.880 --> 00:00:39.439
There's a lot of thank yous that go out.

00:00:39.439 --> 00:00:42.360
First to the core developers of WebR itself.

00:00:42.360 --> 00:00:46.000
So George and Lionel have been absolutely great.

00:00:46.000 --> 00:00:50.080
The second part is thank you so much to the testers.

00:00:50.080 --> 00:00:56.759
So L.A. Holmes and Bob Rudis gave some really great feedback before the extension was released.

00:00:56.759 --> 00:01:05.680
And then in terms of contributors, we've had Joe Yun, or Joe Young, apologies in advance,

00:01:05.680 --> 00:01:07.120
work on some accessibility.

00:01:07.120 --> 00:01:13.040
And then thank you again to the entire Quarto team, not only for the product, but for answering

00:01:13.040 --> 00:01:17.839
my questions and GitHub issues and discussion forum posts.

00:01:17.839 --> 00:01:19.879
So thank you so much.

00:01:19.879 --> 00:01:25.959
With that in mind, a lot of the talk is going to sort of focus here on the main motivation

00:01:25.959 --> 00:01:29.519
for why dynamic documents are really great.

00:01:29.519 --> 00:01:35.480
And that sort of goes with this entire notion of setting up an R environment, and it's not

00:01:35.480 --> 00:01:36.480
really fun.

00:01:36.480 --> 00:01:42.760
It will then sort of move towards looking at the different technologies that will allow

00:01:42.760 --> 00:01:49.360
this environment set up to be a lot easier and sort of create every day as like a day

00:01:49.360 --> 00:01:53.680
one kind of experience for students.

00:01:53.680 --> 00:01:59.360
And then we're going to sort of pivot more to how this can be used inside of education,

00:01:59.360 --> 00:02:02.199
so how you can inform your teaching.

00:02:02.199 --> 00:02:08.440
And we'll also talk just a little, just a super small amount on how you can actually

00:02:08.440 --> 00:02:12.360
use WebR within a research setting.

00:02:12.360 --> 00:02:17.800
It's still really early on, but there's a lot of really exciting things.

00:02:17.800 --> 00:02:24.600
And we'll sort of touch base on some of those perhaps future ideas in the unlocking new

00:02:24.600 --> 00:02:26.600
possibilities part at the end.

00:02:26.600 --> 00:02:31.240
So that being said, let's talk a little bit about our environment setup.

00:02:31.240 --> 00:02:35.919
And the motivating case here was the course that I got a chance to design almost 10 years

00:02:35.919 --> 00:02:41.080
ago now, called Stat 385 at the University of Illinois.

00:02:41.080 --> 00:02:47.720
Back in the day, I sort of thought students would have access to a computer in which they

00:02:47.720 --> 00:02:48.720
can install software.

00:02:48.720 --> 00:02:53.399
It seemed like a very reasonable expectation.

00:02:53.399 --> 00:02:55.880
And then the computing paradigm changed.

00:02:55.880 --> 00:03:02.479
We had tablets enter the market, and we had Chromebooks enter the market.

00:03:02.479 --> 00:03:11.520
So we had all of these systems that sort of required web-based interfaces to sort of have

00:03:11.520 --> 00:03:15.759
students actually experience material.

00:03:15.800 --> 00:03:19.199
So that sort of brings us to that little devil part.

00:03:19.199 --> 00:03:23.039
But that's just one small downside.

00:03:23.039 --> 00:03:29.919
If we take a traditional student that has a laptop, there's usually three steps that

00:03:29.919 --> 00:03:33.880
the student has to do before the first day of class.

00:03:33.880 --> 00:03:37.080
The first one is they have to be able to pick out their operating system.

00:03:37.080 --> 00:03:39.360
So Windows, Mac, or Linux.

00:03:39.360 --> 00:03:45.240
The second part is they have to follow the appropriate R installation recipe.

00:03:45.240 --> 00:03:48.720
And then the third, of course, is to install RStudio.

00:03:48.720 --> 00:03:54.919
So these three together, it's not that bad, maybe.

00:03:54.919 --> 00:03:59.759
But when you start to add in other parts, like if you need developer tools, so if you're

00:03:59.759 --> 00:04:06.679
having students explore compiled code, well, then that opens an entire new level of difficulties

00:04:06.679 --> 00:04:07.679
as well.

00:04:07.679 --> 00:04:12.479
So R tools itself is notorious for changing the installer.

00:04:12.479 --> 00:04:21.760
And on Mac, well, there's more of a community-run installer effort where the compile toolchain

00:04:21.760 --> 00:04:24.239
can easily be set up.

00:04:24.239 --> 00:04:30.920
So students usually at this point are asking, well, why can't I just go to an app store

00:04:30.920 --> 00:04:33.600
and just press the install button?

00:04:33.600 --> 00:04:36.359
Why do I have to go through an installer?

00:04:36.359 --> 00:04:44.600
So it's one of these real sticking points when you're trying to start up a course.

00:04:44.600 --> 00:04:49.760
So the day one class, as a result, sort of goes a little bit like this.

00:04:49.760 --> 00:04:54.140
First, you have that wonderful student that says, how do we install R in RStudio?

00:04:54.140 --> 00:04:59.399
So they didn't get your email, or they didn't have a chance to install it.

00:04:59.399 --> 00:05:04.880
The second student, when they try and run your code, well, they say it doesn't work.

00:05:04.880 --> 00:05:09.000
This could be because they didn't update R, they didn't update RStudio, or they didn't

00:05:09.000 --> 00:05:11.640
put the script in the right spot.

00:05:11.640 --> 00:05:16.040
Another student could just even be using a company computer, right?

00:05:16.040 --> 00:05:19.559
So they don't even have permissions to install anything.

00:05:19.559 --> 00:05:27.179
And then lastly, the student has a really new MacBook, and some software doesn't really

00:05:27.179 --> 00:05:29.720
install appropriately on it.

00:05:29.720 --> 00:05:37.079
So there's so many issues with that day one, you know, starting place to actually have

00:05:37.079 --> 00:05:39.239
people explore data.

00:05:39.239 --> 00:05:44.480
So if we could reimagine what actually this day one looks like, we'd want to go off into

00:05:44.480 --> 00:05:45.480
the cloud.

00:05:45.480 --> 00:05:48.679
So we want to go towards some kind of cloud computing.

00:05:48.679 --> 00:05:53.679
Because the steps here, right, are you would have to log into an environment, you'd have

00:05:53.679 --> 00:05:58.600
to select a project, and then you'd have to start exploring.

00:05:58.600 --> 00:06:04.640
These three steps, super quick, all done inside of a web browser.

00:06:04.640 --> 00:06:08.359
But what if we could drop one of the steps?

00:06:08.359 --> 00:06:12.179
When I say drop one of the steps, I mean, just gently modify.

00:06:12.179 --> 00:06:18.140
So instead of having the student find the project, you could just use a badge.

00:06:18.140 --> 00:06:22.720
So the badge would effectively take you into the login screen, if they're not already logged

00:06:22.720 --> 00:06:23.720
in.

00:06:23.720 --> 00:06:28.720
And then you immediately get them into an environment that's pre set up for you to go

00:06:28.720 --> 00:06:30.579
off and explore.

00:06:30.579 --> 00:06:37.640
This feature of Pulsate Cloud, or in this case, RStudio Cloud before, was really, really

00:06:37.640 --> 00:06:38.640
appealing.

00:06:38.640 --> 00:06:43.399
And it was an amazing thing to experience.

00:06:43.399 --> 00:06:51.760
However, sometimes it's not really practical to be able to have students get into RStudio

00:06:51.760 --> 00:06:52.880
Cloud.

00:06:53.679 --> 00:06:58.239
It could be that, you know, they run out of free compute credits, they can't afford the

00:06:58.239 --> 00:07:02.519
$5 per month limit, so on and so forth.

00:07:02.519 --> 00:07:09.959
So can we figure out a way to sort of recreate this idea of just having them click, and they

00:07:09.959 --> 00:07:14.660
immediately get access to be able to start exploring?

00:07:14.660 --> 00:07:18.160
And this sort of comes through with this technology breakthrough.

00:07:18.640 --> 00:07:24.320
First, we have this really powerful new idea of WebAssembly, which you can sort of think

00:07:24.320 --> 00:07:29.200
about it like Flash in your browser, except way better.

00:07:29.200 --> 00:07:36.079
Or you could think of it like Java applets, which is even way, way better.

00:07:36.079 --> 00:07:41.959
And then we have WebR, which sort of takes huge advantage of this WebAssembly technology

00:07:41.959 --> 00:07:44.959
to allow R to exist in your browser.

00:07:44.959 --> 00:07:48.720
And then last but not least, we have Quarto itself.

00:07:48.720 --> 00:07:53.079
So we're going to really quickly mention why Quarto is really useful.

00:07:53.079 --> 00:08:02.920
So Quarto basically took nine or so different RStudio, or R Markdown packages, and sort

00:08:02.920 --> 00:08:05.200
of unified them together.

00:08:05.200 --> 00:08:07.760
So there's a really great common interface.

00:08:07.760 --> 00:08:11.559
And it also extended the features that were possible.

00:08:11.559 --> 00:08:18.760
So when we start to develop extensions to Quarto, you can really easily switch formats

00:08:18.760 --> 00:08:19.859
without hassle.

00:08:19.859 --> 00:08:25.880
So we can just take this HTML document, and we can immediately plug it right into a website.

00:08:25.880 --> 00:08:27.839
And then we can start serving.

00:08:27.839 --> 00:08:30.799
It's really, really, really nice just for that.

00:08:30.799 --> 00:08:36.520
But as you saw from earlier presentations, there's so many more wonderful features of

00:08:36.520 --> 00:08:38.000
Quarto.

00:08:38.000 --> 00:08:43.919
So that then takes us to the next piece of technology that's really useful.

00:08:43.919 --> 00:08:51.599
Instead of having to go out to post-cloud, what we can do is we can use a compute server.

00:08:51.599 --> 00:08:57.260
Or not, we can use the compute server, but we can move away from this paradigm of needing

00:08:57.260 --> 00:09:02.239
a compute server, where we have R running on that server, and then we have this linked

00:09:02.239 --> 00:09:06.080
connection between R and then the student's computer.

00:09:06.159 --> 00:09:12.640
Instead, what we can do is we can move over to just using any kind of web server that

00:09:12.640 --> 00:09:18.400
if it can serve a file, so that is it can allow a student to download a file, they have

00:09:18.400 --> 00:09:24.840
a working copy of R right in their web browser without sort of us worrying about it.

00:09:24.840 --> 00:09:31.039
So this then takes us to the third huge breakthrough, and that is WebR itself.

00:09:31.039 --> 00:09:36.440
So on the left-hand side, you can see some R code where you're sort of exploring how

00:09:36.440 --> 00:09:38.599
to iterate through items in a list.

00:09:38.599 --> 00:09:46.400
And then on the right side, you can sort of see the same code that would allow you to

00:09:46.400 --> 00:09:50.359
work with R, except directly inside of a web browser.

00:09:50.359 --> 00:09:57.359
So this allows us, again, to just move away from really needing a compute server and just

00:09:57.479 --> 00:10:04.479
sort of having a server that we can use to download files, where if the student has the

00:10:04.479 --> 00:10:11.239
file, then basically they can use R right in their web browser.

00:10:11.239 --> 00:10:14.200
So it might seem a little bit complicated.

00:10:14.200 --> 00:10:21.460
So let's sort of try and show what this unification path really is between these three technologies.

00:10:21.460 --> 00:10:25.880
So to start, we have Querto right inside of RStudio.

00:10:26.039 --> 00:10:30.359
Next, we're going to go ahead and press that render button, and lo and behold, it's going to

00:10:30.359 --> 00:10:33.159
render into an HTML document.

00:10:33.159 --> 00:10:39.880
Now, again, everything that you're seeing inside of the blue rectangle, that's all been

00:10:39.880 --> 00:10:42.599
powered by Querto.

00:10:42.599 --> 00:10:50.799
So if we move over to that idea of needing sort of like a web server, what we can do here is we

00:10:50.799 --> 00:10:58.559
can go out to any place that sort of serves web content in a static context.

00:10:58.559 --> 00:11:04.840
So that is GitHub Pages, Netlify, and even Querto Pub.

00:11:04.840 --> 00:11:13.640
We can immediately place these sort of rendered HTML documents online really quick.

00:11:13.640 --> 00:11:23.080
Now, the next part is we're using WebR itself to have R active inside of the browser.

00:11:23.080 --> 00:11:31.840
So everything inside of the purple rectangle, basically that's all sort of happening because

00:11:31.840 --> 00:11:34.520
WebR exists.

00:11:34.520 --> 00:11:43.280
So where a lot of the dynamic interaction with Querto is coming in, which is one of the huge

00:11:43.280 --> 00:11:50.479
parts of this talk, is really through a Querto extension called Querto WebR, which basically

00:11:50.479 --> 00:11:59.799
puts in a way of taking a code cell and translating it in such a way that it works with

00:11:59.799 --> 00:12:07.840
WebR instead of needing here to actually render a document just with R itself.

00:12:07.840 --> 00:12:15.679
So it's a really, really powerful ecosystem that you're able to come up with as a result.

00:12:15.679 --> 00:12:18.479
So what does this then look like in action?

00:12:18.479 --> 00:12:22.880
Well, what we can do is we can press the run code button.

00:12:22.880 --> 00:12:25.359
We can change values.

00:12:25.359 --> 00:12:29.799
So here we switched from adding to fitting a linear model.

00:12:29.799 --> 00:12:35.599
And now we can even in the same area, we could create a plot.

00:12:35.640 --> 00:12:40.640
So there's a huge level of versatility to what we can do.

00:12:40.640 --> 00:12:49.919
And in terms of making this available, the Querto WebR extension really only needs to be made

00:12:49.919 --> 00:12:54.440
available on the person's computer that's rendering the document.

00:12:54.440 --> 00:13:00.559
So that means that you do need to install a piece of software.

00:13:00.599 --> 00:13:06.039
The easiest way here is just to go on the lower left-hand side of your RStudio window,

00:13:06.039 --> 00:13:10.760
press the terminal tab, which is right next to your console, and then type a quick install

00:13:10.760 --> 00:13:16.400
command of Querto add codeless forward slash Querto dash WebR, press enter.

00:13:16.400 --> 00:13:22.039
And you have two quick prompts to verify that you do indeed want to install the extension.

00:13:22.039 --> 00:13:27.320
So on that end, right, we now sort of have it installed.

00:13:27.359 --> 00:13:36.400
What we can do is we can sort of make our existing HTML documents inside of Querto dynamic

00:13:36.400 --> 00:13:39.599
just by sort of changing four things.

00:13:39.599 --> 00:13:45.479
The first part that we have to change is we have to modify the documents YAML to incorporate

00:13:45.479 --> 00:13:47.000
an engine parameter.

00:13:47.000 --> 00:13:53.760
So if we say engine knitter, this makes sure that all of the code cells are going to be run

00:13:53.760 --> 00:13:56.039
using knitter as the compute engine.

00:13:56.080 --> 00:14:00.479
The alternative here is everything would go through Jupyter, which would require you to

00:14:00.479 --> 00:14:02.559
install more software.

00:14:02.559 --> 00:14:05.559
From there, we need to add a filter.

00:14:05.559 --> 00:14:12.359
This filter, again, is that Querto extension along us to incorporate WebR.

00:14:12.359 --> 00:14:21.159
And then the third part here is we switch the code cell type from R to WebR dash R.

00:14:21.200 --> 00:14:25.760
So once those three are done, we can just render the document.

00:14:25.760 --> 00:14:32.919
And lo and behold, we get an interactive document that we can use just about anywhere that

00:14:32.919 --> 00:14:40.119
there is a static web server host to share our content and have students learn.

00:14:40.119 --> 00:14:43.359
So there's other parts to this as well.

00:14:43.359 --> 00:14:45.559
Again, there's a lot of different options.

00:14:45.559 --> 00:14:48.159
You can modify WebR's options.

00:14:48.159 --> 00:14:51.840
You can even change the extension options yourself.

00:14:51.840 --> 00:14:54.919
There's a bunch of customization options.

00:14:54.919 --> 00:15:01.640
One of the huge parts here that I'll just point out is you really can improve the user

00:15:01.640 --> 00:15:07.479
experience if you put up at the top of your document the kinds of packages that are

00:15:07.479 --> 00:15:14.000
required, because that sort of allows the document to load with all of your software

00:15:14.000 --> 00:15:20.719
available in comparison to just having them interactively install a package for each code

00:15:20.719 --> 00:15:22.320
cell that's needed.

00:15:22.320 --> 00:15:25.559
So there's, again, a lot of options that you have.

00:15:25.559 --> 00:15:33.000
Feel free to check out the Querto WebR extension documentation online.

00:15:33.000 --> 00:15:37.840
Now, the other part here, really quick, is the context.

00:15:37.960 --> 00:15:45.280
So context allows us to basically have this level of interactivity.

00:15:45.280 --> 00:15:46.799
So we can run code.

00:15:46.799 --> 00:15:50.479
We can also create an output, right, so output only.

00:15:50.479 --> 00:15:56.159
And then we have a setup, and the setup is largely left empty.

00:15:56.159 --> 00:16:05.280
So when it comes to education, these parts allow us to just have these ready-to-go exercises.

00:16:05.280 --> 00:16:07.400
So we have the what-if scenario.

00:16:07.400 --> 00:16:10.119
We have a fill-in-the-blank kind of approach.

00:16:10.119 --> 00:16:16.159
And we can have it work about anywhere, which is really, really powerful.

00:16:16.159 --> 00:16:17.440
There are always limits.

00:16:17.440 --> 00:16:23.960
The first limit here is this very much so requires an internet connection at the start.

00:16:23.960 --> 00:16:32.719
Not all the packages are available, and it's not really a replacement for VDS code or RStudio.

00:16:32.719 --> 00:16:40.559
But the other part that's really useful here is you start to actually see student behavior like never before.

00:16:40.559 --> 00:16:49.159
So we can actually see how students are going through and learning from the document just by adding here a short code.

00:16:49.159 --> 00:16:53.440
This also works with books, too, in the Querto format.

00:16:53.440 --> 00:17:01.359
So generally, students spent about 1.5 times more on dynamic documents.

00:17:01.359 --> 00:17:06.800
They frequently interacted with code cells where the outcome wasn't immediately clear in their mind.

00:17:06.800 --> 00:17:12.280
And they really described this approach as being more modern compared to old-fashioned.

00:17:12.280 --> 00:17:16.560
So they generally have liked it quite a bit.

00:17:16.560 --> 00:17:30.239
In terms of that research part, well, research-wise, not necessarily quite to the point where you can really compile your own R package.

00:17:30.280 --> 00:17:33.079
That's not on CRAN in an easy sense.

00:17:33.079 --> 00:17:42.839
But if it is on CRAN, which you should always strive to put your research on to CRAN, it actually might even be available right now inside of WebR,

00:17:42.839 --> 00:17:53.119
which means that you can really quickly take this R code that you've developed and you can include a reproducible link to your Querto notebook alongside of the paper.

00:17:53.119 --> 00:17:57.040
No longer do you need the static file.

00:17:57.040 --> 00:17:59.640
Now, there's a few new possibilities as well.

00:17:59.640 --> 00:18:01.800
One of the huge things here is Reveal.js.

00:18:01.800 --> 00:18:03.560
That's a little bit problematic.

00:18:03.560 --> 00:18:05.359
We do need to improve the interface.

00:18:05.359 --> 00:18:10.640
And then lastly, we want to sort of also explore a little bit with Pyoid.

00:18:10.640 --> 00:18:19.599
So here you can sort of see a quick Pyoid demo, which basically allows us to run Python as well.

00:18:19.599 --> 00:18:21.719
There's a lot more.

00:18:21.719 --> 00:18:32.079
If you are interested, again, there's some really great resources, the extension, the project, and the community overall for WebR is really growing rapidly.

00:18:32.079 --> 00:18:34.560
And we'd love to have you here with us.

00:18:34.560 --> 00:18:35.599
So thank you so much.

00:18:35.599 --> 00:18:37.760
I'm sorry if I went over.

00:18:37.760 --> 00:18:40.280
If there's any questions, I'm more than happy to take them now.

00:18:40.280 --> 00:18:43.000
Or feel free to reach out and just contact me with them.

00:18:43.400 --> 00:18:45.079
Thank you.

00:18:45.079 --> 00:18:46.079
Thank you.

00:18:46.079 --> 00:18:47.079
Lovely.

00:18:47.079 --> 00:18:48.079
Thank you.

00:18:48.079 --> 00:18:49.079
Can you hear me?

00:18:49.079 --> 00:18:50.079
Excellent.

00:18:50.079 --> 00:19:01.280
I'm going to ask you one question, because people are impressed and thinking about starting

00:19:01.280 --> 00:19:02.760
to convert to stuff.

00:19:02.760 --> 00:19:12.839
So the obvious question is how stable would you say that WebR extension API is?

00:19:12.839 --> 00:19:24.239
So I would say as long as you're not trying to do any kind of direct changes to the WebR

00:19:24.239 --> 00:19:27.719
instance that we have, you should be fine.

00:19:27.719 --> 00:19:32.719
So I would say we're not planning on really changing that context option.

00:19:32.719 --> 00:19:38.199
There's only really one kind of component that you have, and that is really that context

00:19:38.199 --> 00:19:42.420
option that could potentially change at this point.

00:19:42.420 --> 00:19:49.060
We will upgrade the extension as new versions of R and WebR become available.

00:19:49.060 --> 00:19:53.579
So that part is just part of the natural process.

00:19:53.579 --> 00:20:00.219
I can't guarantee what you're changing would break or not break.

00:20:00.219 --> 00:20:06.219
Chances are the code that you're running, it should be fine, is my hope.

00:20:06.859 --> 00:20:13.619
Because of how this is done, each extension version, it's basically locked.

00:20:13.619 --> 00:20:18.260
